      <h1 class="display-4">AI in Dental Diagnostics</h1>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Main content container -->
  <div class="container my-5">

    <!-- Introductory paragraph -->
    <section id="introduction" class="mb-5">
      <p class="lead">
        AI in dental diagnostics leverages advanced image analysis and machine learning to improve early detection of oral diseases. By analyzing dental images (X-rays, CT scans, photos) at scale, AI systems can highlight pathologies such as cavities (dental caries) and bone loss with high precision. This enhances diagnostic accuracy and efficiency, reducing the likelihood of missed conditions and leading to better patient outcomes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Diagram/flow section -->
    <section id="flow-diagram" class="mb-5">
      <div class="text-center">
        <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/4270367/pexels-photo-4270367.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&h=650&w=940" class="img-fluid rounded shadow mb-3" alt="Dental X-ray on tablet for AI analysis">
      </div>
      <p>
        A typical AI diagnostic pipeline begins with a dental image (e.g. X-ray) as input. The image is then processed by segmentation models that identify key structures and potential lesions (e.g. isolating each tooth and highlighting areas of decay). Finally, the model outputs a diagnosis or highlight of suspected conditions (such as caries or bone loss), which assists the clinician in decision-making.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Use cases cards grid -->
    <section id="use-cases" class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="text-syrian-green mb-4">AI Use Cases in Dental Diagnostics</h2>
      <div class="row row-cols-1 row-cols-md-2 row-cols-lg-4 g-4">
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card h-100 card-hover">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">Caries Detection</h5>
              <p class="card-text">
                AI models can detect dental caries (cavities) on radiographs, often identifying early-stage lesions that are easy to miss visually. Studies report high sensitivity for AI-based caries detection, matching or exceeding human performance.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card h-100 card-hover">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">Bone Loss Assessment</h5>
              <p class="card-text">
                Automated analysis can quantify periodontal bone loss from dental X-rays, aiding in periodontal disease screening. Convolutional networks have demonstrated the ability to identify and measure bone resorption around teeth, supporting early intervention.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card h-100 card-hover">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">Lesion Identification</h5>
              <p class="card-text">
                AI helps detect radiographic lesions such as apical abscesses or tumors. Research shows deep learning models can reliably pick out pathologies like apical lesions on X-rays, flagging cases for further review.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card h-100 card-hover">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">Comparative Analysis</h5>
              <p class="card-text">
                Comparative studies benchmark AI against clinicians. For example, one study found an AI caries detection system and dental examiners had nearly identical accuracy (around 88%), with no statistically significant difference. This suggests AI can serve as a valuable adjunct to clinical evaluation.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- AI tools section -->
    <section id="ai-tools" class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="text-syrian-green mb-3">Real-world Dental AI Tools</h2>
      <p>
        Several commercial AI products are now available for dental imaging:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pearl (Second Opinion):</strong> Uses computer vision to identify a wide range of pathological and restorative features on dental radiographs, providing decision support for dentists.</li>
        <li><strong>Overjet:</strong> Provides AI-powered analysis of dental X-rays to highlight conditions like bone loss and caries. Overjet’s AI is widely used in clinical settings.</li>
        <li><strong>Diagnocat:</strong> An AI platform that analyzes 2D X-rays and 3D CBCT scans to detect cavities, periodontal disease, and other oral pathologies. (Note: Diagnocat is not yet FDA-cleared.)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Read More collapsible section -->
    <section id="read-more" class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="text-syrian-green mb-3">Read More</h2>
      <div class="mb-3">
        <button class="btn btn-secondary" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#moreContent" aria-expanded="false">
          Toggle Details
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="collapse" id="moreContent">
        <div class="card card-body">
          <p>
            Advanced AI models in dentistry often rely on deep convolutional neural networks trained on large annotated datasets. These models can significantly improve the accuracy of radiographic interpretation, as they learn subtle features of dental anatomy and pathology. However, current research also emphasizes challenges: e.g., ensuring robustness across different imaging devices and patient populations, and addressing data privacy and integration into clinical workflows.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

